        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Although by tapering the SMA data to a lower resolution of ~5.0'', we managed to have the methanol lines “detected” tentatively in regions remote from IRS 46 (Fig. 2), chances are we may be seeing the methanol emission from the surrounding cloud rather than IRS 46 itself. The true methanol emission from IRS 46 disk may be too weak to be detected by the SMA due to low sensitivity and beam dilution; this is quite likely as IRS 46 is still unresolved in both thermal dust continuum and formaldehyde emission even at SMA (3.5''×2.2'') resolution. Such reasoning may also be applied to our SMT single-dish observations and to all the six other disk-containing protostars! This is exactly the reason that motivated us to propose high sensitivity and resolution ALMA observations to confirm the existence of COMs in protoplanetary disks.

By comparing the methanol spectra in Figs. 1 and 5, we find immediately that most CH3OH lines, at the same transition and observed with the same SMT telescope, all appear to have similar line intensities to each other. Therefore, we may use IRS 46 to represent all our target sources for the sensitivity argument followed. The SMA methanol spectrum taken at the exact center position of IRS 46 (not shown) disclosed that the two strongest methanol transitions were not detected with an rms noise of ~50 mJy/bm. The major goal of our proposed experiment is to find the most representative COM, i.e., CH3OH, in disks. Now, if we assume there exist indeed methanol in the disk, the expected CH3OH line intensity should be &lt; 50 mJy/bm. For a secure detection, we thus require an rms of 10 mJy/bm at 0”.25 resolution in the extended configuration for a 5-σ detection with reasonable margin. The expected CH3OH linewidth is ~1.0 km/s (Fig. 5) so we will employ a correlator setup with a bandwidth of 468.75 MHz at 244.141 kHz resolution (or 0.15 km/s channel spacing). Table 1 gives more details of our spectral setup including the major H2CO and CH3OH lines in Band 6.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
