    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>A number of Class 0 sources have been shown to be rich in organic molecules. However, most of the interstellar material accreted during the Class-0 phase is consumed by the forming protostar, a more meaningful comparison between interstellar and comet chemistries can only begin to be made by studying the composition of the envelopes and disks of Class I sources. In addition, astrochemical studies of molecular species in protoplanetary disks allow us to learn more on their chemical compositions hence the physical processes on planet formation. In particular, as Class II T-Tauri star lacks a surrounding gas envelope and molecular outflows, observing the gaseous component of organic molecules which surely reside in the T-Tauri disks will enable us to determine the efficiency of protoplanetary disks, similar to our Solar Nebula, to synthesize prebiotically important COMs (complex organic molecules). A detection of organic molecules in Class II disks would play a pivotal role in connecting the missing link between Class I sources and the pre-Solar Nebula.</prp:abstract>
